<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO CHRIS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar 15 12:05:10 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chris,<br><br>
You said-<br><br>
&gt;&quot;Don't you guys realize that Americans today respect, honor and sympathize with Vietnam Vets?&quot;&lt;<br><br>
Would you believe, and I can only speak for myself, *no*?<br><br>
I bet that sounds really strange. From where you are sitting, the next obvious thoughts might be &quot;I don't believe it!&quot; or &quot;Why?&quot;.<br><br>
There are some very good reasons why, and they are all based in psychology.<br><br>
Many Vietnam Veterans, including myself, are afflicted in varying degrees with Post Traumatic Stress Disorder, PTSD. Until a few years ago, I believed PTSD was mythology, until my head came unglued, I found myself flashing back to Nam in real time, and I was on the most amazing mental roller coaster ride I have ever experienced. To keep the story short, after a lot of work with mental health professionals, and a psychoeducational course in PTSD, I discovered, and was also told, that I have had PTSD since I returned from Nam. I just did not realize it. Reality &quot;shifts&quot; around with this thing. In addition, some of the effects of PTSD are a foreshortened sense of the future, complete mistrust of everything, social isolation, messed up personal relationships, and a whole list of other really not so nice things.<br><br>
I said to Alex-<br><br>
&gt;&quot;Are may of us locked in our own &quot;time warp&quot;? I, personally, did not know what to expect when I started posting on this site many months ago, having kept it all inside myself for all these years. It has taken me a lot of work over the past few years just to arrive at this point.&quot;&lt;<br><br>
Do you see how those words fit?<br><br>
I have, at many levels, been fighting the Vietnam War over and over in my mind. Survival strategies and combat techniques insidiously survive although the reality of their <br>
necessity is no longer manifest. In short, I stuffed it all. <br>
I stuffed it all to survive. I was never deprogrammed. I am told I am one of the lucky ones. Being known as a &quot;Darth Vader&quot; in my profession, and having a generally messed up life, is better, I guess, than alcohol or drug addiction and sleeping under a bridge.<br><br>
Chris, there is no way on earth you could see into some of the dialog on these sites and not come away confused if you were not aware of some of what I have just spoken.<br><br>
For me, the Vietnam War is truly &quot;the gift that keeps on giving&quot;.<br><br>
Right now I am like one of those dime store turtles (which are no longer sold) poking out my head to check out the world, knowing full well I have a shell into which I can retreat at a moments notice. The trick is to learn I no longer need the shell!<br><br>
Intellectually, your arguments and thoughts are flawless, and I really appreciate the time you took to express them. Emotionally, I have to merge with them, and learn to trust again.<br><br>
Arthur<br><br>
